Purpose
Revenue tells you how much the business earned. Retention tells you how healthy the business actually is. A company can show strong monthly sales while quietly losing its customer base — and not notice until the pipeline runs dry. This dashboard exists to catch that signal early and give decision-makers the visibility to act on it.

What This Dashboard Measures
1. Overall Retention & Churn Rate
The headline metrics — what percentage of customers returned for a second purchase versus those who bought once and never came back. These two numbers together define the loyalty health of the business at a glance.
2. Retained vs Churned Customer Count
Absolute numbers behind the percentages — how many unique customers fall into each group, tracked over time to identify whether retention is improving or declining month over month.
3. Customer List by Status
A drillable table of individual customers segmented by Retained and Churned status, showing their region, segment, total orders, total revenue contributed, and last order date. This turns an aggregate metric into an actionable list.
4. Retention by Region
Breaks down retention and churn rates across East, West, North, and South regions — revealing whether loyalty is consistent geographically or whether specific regions are losing customers at a higher rate than others.
5. Retention by Segment
Compares Consumer versus Corporate customer behaviour — Corporate customers typically show different retention patterns due to procurement cycles, while Consumer behaviour is more impulse and season driven.
6. Retention by Product Category
Identifies whether Technology or Accessories buyers are more likely to return — helping the business understand which product experiences drive loyalty and which ones result in one-time purchases.
7. Monthly Retention Trend
Tracks how retention rate moves across months, highlighting seasonal dips (May) and peaks (December) — and whether the business is retaining the surge of December customers into the following months.
8. Revenue from Retained vs Churned Customers
Quantifies the financial impact of retention — showing how much revenue is generated by loyal customers versus one-time buyers, making the business case for investing in retention strategies.

Key Metrics at a Glance
MetricDAX MeasureBusiness QuestionRetention RateRetained ÷ Total Customers × 100What % of customers came back?Churn RateChurned ÷ Total Customers × 100What % did we lose?Retained CustomersDISTINCTCOUNT where orders > 1How many loyal customers do we have?Churned CustomersDISTINCTCOUNT where orders = 1How many bought once and left?Revenue from RetainedSUM Revenue where Status = RetainedHow much do loyal customers contribute?Avg Orders per Retained CustomerTotal Orders ÷ Retained CustomersHow frequently do loyal customers buy?

How to Read This Dashboard
Start with the headline numbers — Retention Rate and Churn Rate cards give you the immediate health signal. A retention rate above 50% is a positive indicator for a business at this scale.
Move to the trend line — if retention is declining month over month, that is more concerning than a low single-month number. Direction matters more than a snapshot.
Use the region and segment breakdowns to identify where the problem is concentrated. A high overall churn rate looks very different if it is driven entirely by one region or one segment — because the solution is then targeted, not broad.
Drill into the customer table to move from aggregate to individual — identify your highest-value churned customers and assess whether a win-back campaign makes financial sense.

Business Insight This Dashboard Delivers

Retaining an existing customer costs significantly less than acquiring a new one. A business with a 60% retention rate has a fundamentally more stable revenue base than one with 30% retention — even if their total sales figures look similar today. This dashboard makes the retention picture visible, measurable, and actionable so that customer loyalty becomes a managed metric rather than an assumed outcome.


